<p>Premium Cabernet Sauvignon from renowned producers like <strong>Screaming Eagle, Château Latour, or Penfolds Bin 707</strong> can age gracefully for 20-30 years or more. Mid-tier bottles from respected estates typically peak at 10-15 years, while everyday Cabernet Sauvignon is best consumed within 3-5 years of vintage.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Peak Drinking Windows</h3>

<p>Young Cabernet Sauvignon displays intense blackcurrant fruit and firm tannins from compounds like catechins and proanthocyanidins. Over time, these tannins polymerize and soften, while primary fruit flavors evolve into <strong>complex tertiary notes of cedar, tobacco, leather, and graphite</strong>. Premium bottles often hit their stride between 8-12 years, when fruit concentration balances perfectly with developed complexity.</p>

<p>The wine's color shifts from deep purple-black to garnet and eventually brick-red as anthocyanins break down and sediment forms.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>

<p>Store bottles on their side at <strong>55-58°F (13-14°C)</strong> with 70% humidity to prevent cork desiccation. Maintain darkness and minimal vibration—UV light degrades wine compounds and movement disturbs sediment formation.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>

<p>Well-aged Cabernet Sauvignon shows clear liquid with natural sediment, developing bouquet complexity while maintaining fruit integrity. Warning signs include:</p>

