<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Napa Valley and Bordeaux Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon tends to be fuller-bodied with riper, more concentrated dark fruit flavors and higher alcohol (14-15%), while Bordeaux Cabernet typically shows more restraint with earthier, mineral-driven characteristics and lower alcohol (12.5-14%). Napa wines often emphasize pure varietal expression, whereas Bordeaux Cabernet is usually blended with Merlot and Cabernet Franc for complexity. Climate differences mean Napa produces consistently ripe fruit, while Bordeaux expressions vary significantly by vintage.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I know if a Cabernet Sauvignon is worth aging or drinking now?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young Cabernet Sauvignon with firm tannins, high acidity, and concentrated fruit will benefit from 5-15 years of aging, while wines with softer tannins and lower acidity are best enjoyed within 3-5 years. Look for structural indicators like grip on your palate and whether the wine feels "closed" or tight when first opened. Premium examples from renowned vintages (like 2016 Napa or 2016 Bordeaux) often need at least 5 years to show their full potential, while entry-level Cabernet is typically made for immediate enjoyment.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What food pairings work best with high-quality Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium Cabernet Sauvignon pairs exceptionally well with rich, protein-heavy dishes that can match its intensity—think dry-aged ribeye, braised short ribs, or lamb with rosemary. The wine's tannins help cut through fat, while its dark fruit complements savory, umami-rich flavors like aged cheeses, mushrooms, and grilled meats. Avoid delicate fish or light poultry, as the wine's power will overwhelm subtle flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Cabernet Sauvignon a good choice for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Cabernet Sauvignon can be challenging for absolute beginners due to its pronounced tannins and often high alcohol, but it's excellent for those ready to explore serious red wines. Start with fruit-forward examples from warmer climates like California's Central Coast or Chile's Colchagua Valley, which tend to have softer tannins and more approachable flavors. Avoid highly tannic, austere examples from cooler regions until your palate develops a tolerance for structure.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best temperature to serve premium Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve premium Cabernet Sauvignon at 60-65°F (15-18°C) to showcase its complexity while avoiding the muting effects of being too cold or the alcohol burn of being too warm. This temperature allows the wine's aromatics to open fully while keeping tannins smooth and integrated. If your wine has been stored in a cool cellar, let it warm up for 30-45 minutes before serving, or briefly warm the bowl of your glass with your hands.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How can I find the best value in Cabernet Sauvignon without overspending?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Cabernet Sauvignon from emerging regions like Columbia Valley Washington, Mendoza Argentina, or South Africa's Stellenbosch, which often deliver premium quality at 30-50% less than Napa equivalents. Seek out second labels from prestigious producers (like Faust from Huneeus or Liberty School from Caymus) and consider excellent vintages from 3-5 years ago that may be discounted. Avoid wines under $15, as quality Cabernet Sauvignon requires significant investment in viticulture and winemaking.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes people make when buying expensive Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is buying cult Cabernet Sauvignon too young and drinking it immediately, wasting hundreds of dollars on wines that need years to develop. Many buyers also fall for inflated pricing based purely on reputation rather than vintage quality—a poor vintage from a famous producer isn't worth premium pricing. Another error is storing expensive Cabernet upright or in warm conditions, which can ruin a costly investment within months.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What alternatives should I consider if I love Cabernet Sauvignon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">If you enjoy Cabernet Sauvignon's structure and dark fruit, explore Malbec from Argentina for similar intensity with softer tannins, or try Bordeaux-style blends that include Cabernet with Merlot and Cabernet Franc. For something different but equally complex, consider Barolo or Barbaresco from Italy, which offer similar aging potential and food-pairing versatility. Super Tuscans also provide Cabernet-based blends with unique Italian terroir expression.</p>
  </div>
